Real Estate Price Prediction

Data Source:
Taiwan real estate price prediction dataset, Quant Bruce.
Retrieved from https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/quantbruce/real-estate-price-prediction/data

In this analysis, I used a multiple linear regression model to predict house prices based on features such as house age, distance to the nearest MRT station, number of nearby convenience stores, and geographic coordinates (latitude and longitude). I cleaned the dataset, handled outliers, performed feature scaling and multicollinearity checks, and evaluated the model on unseen test data. The model was implemented using scikit-learn in Python.

Preprocessing¶

Exploring the descriptive statistics of the variables¶

This dataset contains 414 records of house sales in Taiwan, with the goal of predicting house price of unit area using various property and location features. The average price per unit area is around 38, but values range widely from 7.6 to 117.5, indicating high variation. A few very high-priced houses suggest the presence of outliers that could affect modeling. The average house age is about 18 years, ranging from newly built to over 43 years old, and it likely has a negative relationship with price — older houses tend to cost less per unit area. Distance to the nearest MRT station ranges from 0 to over 6. The number of convenience stores nearby averages 4 (ranging from 0 to 10) and is expected to increase property value, as more stores usually indicate better access to amenities. The latitude and longitude show that all properties are within a relatively small geographic area, but even small differences in location can impact housing prices, making these features important for spatial analysis. Lastly, the transaction dates fall within a narrow period (mid-2012 to mid-2013), so this feature provides little variability and can likely be excluded from the model.

Determining the variables of interest¶

I removed two columns: 'No' and 'X1 transaction date'. The No column is just an index and doesn’t contain useful information. The transaction date, while technically a feature, spans only a short period (mid-2012 to mid-2013) and doesn't provide enough variation to be helpful for prediction. Dropping both helps keep the dataset clean and focused on meaningful variables.

Dealing with outliers¶

The histogram above shows the distribution of house price per unit area (in NT$ per ping). Most values fall between 20 and 60, with a noticeable peak around 40. However, we can also see that the distribution is slightly right-skewed, with a few properties priced above 80, and even beyond 100.

These extremely high prices are considered outliers — they are very different from the majority of the data and may not reflect typical market conditions. If left in the dataset, they can distort the regression model, pulling the line of best fit toward them and reducing overall accuracy for the rest of the predictions.

To create a more balanced model that better represents most properties, I decided to remove the top 1% of highest-priced data points. This helps reduce skew and improve the model’s performance and stability.

After applying a log transformation to the MRT distance feature, the relationship between this variable and house price per unit area becomes more linear and easier to interpret. The second plot in the figure ("Price and distance to the nearest MRT station") now shows a clearer negative trend, indicating that as the (log) distance to the MRT station increases, the property price tends to decrease. This transformation helps reduce the skewness and compress the extreme values, making the pattern more stable for linear regression.

In the other scatter plots, we observe the following:

House age continues to show a weak negative relationship with price, though it's scattered — older houses tend to have lower prices per unit area, but not strictly.

Number of convenience stores displays a loose positive relationship — generally, more stores nearby are associated with higher prices.

Latitude and longitude clearly show that price varies by location. There are dense clusters indicating more expensive neighborhoods, highlighting the spatial influence on property value.

Overall, the log transformation improves the interpretability of the MRT feature and makes the dataset more suitable for a linear regression model. The other features remain valuable and show logical relationships with the target variable.

from statsmodels.stats.outliers_influence import variance_inflation_factor
variables = data_cleaned[['X2 house age','X4 number of convenience stores','X5 latitude','X6 longitude','log_mrt_distance']]
vif = pd.DataFrame()
vif["VIF"] = [variance_inflation_factor(variables.values, i) for i in range(variables.shape[1])]
vif["Features"] = variables.columns

To ensure the reliability of our regression model, we performed a multicollinearity check using the Variance Inflation Factor (VIF). Multicollinearity occurs when two or more independent variables are highly correlated with each other, making it difficult for the model to estimate their individual effects accurately. High multicollinearity can lead to unstable coefficients, inflated standard errors, and misleading interpretations. Upon further inspection, we found that log_mrt_distance is strongly correlated with latitude and longitude, which makes sense — houses closer to MRT stations tend to be concentrated in specific geographic areas. Because latitude and longitude provide richer spatial information, we decided to drop log_mrt_distance to reduce redundancy and improve model stability.

This step helps ensure our model is both interpretable and statistically sound.

Linear regression model¶

Declare the inputs and the targets¶

In [43]:
targets = data_cleaned['Y house price of unit area']
inputs = data_cleaned.drop(['Y house price of unit area'],axis=1)

Scale the data¶

Before training the regression model, we apply feature scaling using StandardScaler from scikit-learn. This process standardizes the input features by removing the mean and scaling them to unit variance — in other words, it transforms each feature to have a mean of 0 and a standard deviation of 1.

We do this because the input features in our dataset (such as distance, house age, and geographic coordinates) are on very different scales. For example, the distance to MRT might be in the thousands, while latitude is a small decimal number. If left unscaled, features with larger values could dominate the model and distort the results, even though they may not be more important.

By calling scaler.fit(inputs), we instruct the scaler to learn the mean and standard deviation of each feature in the training data. These values are then used to transform the data consistently, ensuring all features contribute equally to the model.

In [45]:
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
scaler = StandardScaler()
scaler.fit(inputs)

inputs_scaled = scaler.transform(inputs)

Train Test Split¶

In this step, we use train_test_split from sklearn.model_selection to divide our dataset into a training set and a test set. Specifically, we apply an 80/20 split, where 80% of the data is used to train the regression model, and the remaining 20% is reserved for testing the model's performance on unseen data.

This separation is essential in supervised learning because it allows us to evaluate how well the model generalizes — that is, how accurately it can make predictions on data it hasn't seen before. Without this split, we could end up building a model that performs well on training data but poorly in real-world scenarios (a problem known as overfitting).

In [48]:
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(inputs_scaled, targets, test_size=0.2, random_state=365)

The table above summarizes the weights (or coefficients) assigned to each feature by the linear regression model. These values indicate the strength and direction of the relationship between each independent variable and the house price per unit area. A negative weight, such as the one for house age (-3.05), suggests that as houses get older, their price per unit area tends to decrease. In contrast, the number of convenience stores has a strong positive weight (+5.03), indicating that properties located near more stores are generally more expensive. The positive weights for both latitude (+3.76) and longitude (+3.00) suggest that location plays a significant role in determining house prices — with properties situated further north and east tending to be priced higher. Since the features were standardized before training, these weights reflect the change in predicted price per unit area for every one standard deviation increase in the corresponding feature, helping us interpret the relative importance and influence of each input variable.

This scatter plot compares the predicted house prices (y_hat_test) to the actual prices (y_test) from the test set. Each point represents one observation, with the true value on the x-axis and the predicted value on the y-axis.

Ideally, all points should align closely along an imaginary diagonal line (45-degree line), which would indicate perfect predictions. In this plot, we observe a positive trend, showing that the model is generally able to predict higher prices for more expensive houses and lower prices for cheaper ones. However, the points are somewhat scattered, particularly for lower and higher values, suggesting that the model may struggle slightly with extreme cases.

This plot provides a visual way to evaluate the generalization performance of the model on unseen data — how well it performs beyond the training set. Although not perfect, the pattern suggests that the model has learned a reasonable mapping from the input features to the target variable.

Conclution¶

This multiple linear regression model was developed to predict house price per unit area based on features such as house age, proximity to MRT stations, number of nearby convenience stores, and geographic location. After cleaning and transforming the data — including handling outliers and addressing multicollinearity — the final model demonstrated a reasonable fit, with an R² score of approximately 0.61 on the training data. Most features showed meaningful relationships with the target, such as a negative impact from house age and positive contributions from nearby stores and location.

The residual analysis confirmed that errors are generally well distributed and centered around zero, supporting the model’s assumptions. While the model performs reliably in most cases, a few predictions resulted in significant errors, indicating the need for further refinement if high precision is required. Overall, the model is a solid baseline for predicting housing prices and offers clear insights into the most influential factors affecting property value in this dataset.
